{"cursor":"2899","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"In Roman mythology, 'Camilla' of the Volsci was the daughter of King Metabus and\nCasmilla. Driven from his throne, Metabus was chased into the wilderness by\narmed Volsci, his infant daughter in his hands. The river Amasenus blocked his\npath, and, fearing for the child's welfare, Metabus bound her to a spear. He\npromised Diana that Camilla would be her servant, a warrior virgin. He then\nsafely threw her to the other side, and swam across to retrieve her. The baby\nCamilla was suckled by a mare, and once her \"first firm steps had [been] taken,\nthe small palms were armed with a keen javelin; her sire a bow and quiver from\nher shoulder slung.\" Virgil, [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=-\nPerseus%3Atext%3A1999.02.0054%3Abook%3D11%3Acard%3D557 11.570 ff.]. She\nwas raised in her childhood to be a huntress and kept the companionship of her\nfather and the shepherds in the hills and woods.\n\nThe river 'Amasenus' is said to have been used by Virgil as a poetic reference\nto the Amazons with whom Camilla is associated. http://books.google.com/books?id=o5-\n3qxjL6lgC&pg=PA378&lpg=PA378&dq=virgil+camilla+reference+river+spear&source=bl&-\nots=JrIfA1bWRu&sig=Jge6Thh3LYwEIEWEB5ab8ynjmjQ&hl=en&sa=X&ei=im4_Uc7JCYy1Pfi0ga-\nAF&ved=0CFkQ6AEwBw#v=onepage&q=virgil%20camilla%20reference%20river%20spear&f=f-\nalse\n\nIn the [[Aeneid]], she helped her ally, King Turnus of the Rutuli, fight Aeneas\nand the Trojans in the war sparked by the courting of Princess Lavinia. Arruns,\na Trojan ally, stalked Camilla on the battlefield, and, when she was opportunely\ndistracted by her pursuit of Chloreus, killed her. Virgil, [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/cgi-\nbin//ptext?lookup=Verg.+A.+11.725 11.1121–1210] Diana's attendant,\nOpis, at her mistress' behest, avenged Camilla's death by slaying\nArruns. Virgil, [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/cgi-\nbin/ptext?lookup=Verg.+A.+11.836 11.1236–1256]. Virgil claimed that\nCamilla once ran so swiftly she could run over a field of wheat without breaking\nthe tops of the plants or across the seas without wetting her feet. Virgil,\n[http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/cgi-bin/ptext?lookup=Verg.+A.+7.803\n7.1094–1103].\n\nCamilla is similar to Penthesilea of Greek mythology. Virgil, The Aeneid,\ntrans. Robert Fagles, Penguin Books, 2006, p. 438.\n","linknr":127,"url":"Camilla_(mythology)","recorded":1375089313,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Camilla_(mythology)&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Camilla_(mythology)&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/Roman_mythology","/wiki/Volsci","/wiki/Metabus","/wiki/Diana_(mythology)","#cite_note-1","/wiki/Amazons","#cite_note-2","/wiki/Aeneid","/wiki/Turnus","/wiki/Rutuli","/wiki/Aeneas","/wiki/Lavinia","#cite_note-3","/wiki/Nereid","#cite_note-4","/wiki/Virgil","#cite_note-5","/wiki/Penthesilea","/wiki/Greek_mythology","#cite_note-6","/w/index.php?title=Camilla_(mythology)&action=edit&section=1","#cite_ref-1","http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.02.0054%3Abook%3D11%3Acard%3D557","#cite_ref-2","http://books.google.com/books?id=o5-3qxjL6lgC&pg=PA378&lpg=PA378&dq=virgil+camilla+reference+river+spear&source